        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Nunc dem&ugrave;m, Romanorum Imperatorum maximus, Scipio: et admirabilium victoriarum ingenti gloria, soli ex omnibus mundi summis 
                        Ducibus, secundus Alexandro Magno.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                <person name="Alexander the Great"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Now at last there is Scipio, the greatest of the Roman commanders; and with his immense honor of wonderful victories, second to Alexander the 
                Great alone, out of all the greatest leaders of the world.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="Annibal">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Analysis aciei Annibalis; singulari arte instructa[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Hannibal"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                An analysis of Hannibalâ€™s battle line, which was constructed with extraordinary skill.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="conditiones pacis dictae">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Conditiones Pacis, post tam immanem victoriam. honorifica[e] conditiones pro tempore: nec tam violenta[e], aut superba[e], qu&agrave;m metuere
                        poterant ita victi.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                The terms for peace, after such a massive victory. Honorific terms for the time being. And not so extreme or arrogant as those who were 
                defeated in this way could have feared.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
